    <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="245">
      <subfield code="a">Real-space cluster dynamical mean-field approach to the Falicov-Kimball model: An alloy-analogy approach</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="260">
      <subfield code="c">2017-03-13</subfield>
      <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="300">
      <subfield code="a">10</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
      <subfield code="a">It is long known that the best single-site coherent potential approximation falls short of describing Anderson localization. Here, we study a binary alloy disorder [or equivalently, a spinless Falicov-Kimball (FK)] model and construct a dominantly analytic cluster extension that treats intracluster (1/d,d= spatial dimension) correlations exactly. We find that, in general, the irreducible two-particle vertex exhibits clear nonanalyticities before the band splitting transition of the Hubbard type occurs, signaling onset of an unusual type of localization at strong coupling. Using time-dependent response to a sudden local quench as a diagnostic, we find that the long-time wave-function overlap changes from a power-law to an anomalous form at strong coupling, lending additional support to this idea. Our results also imply such “strong” localization in the equivalent FK model, the simplest interacting fermion system.</subfield>
